Chet, Tom, Thank You both. I am honored to be considered part of your support team, likewise, you too have taught me lessons that grad school, and the streets overlooked.<br>
  <br>
Chris, you are a trip.  So young, so new, I am not sure what to make of you yet, but I am working on it.<br><br>
Re: PTSD. As a shrink, I know it existed because it was in a magical book of labels, the holy &quot;DSM&quot;. Not the first or second editions however, not until DSM 3 did it become a recognizable disorder with a checklist of symptoms. In DSM 4, written by the American Psychiatric Assoc., did it finally reach a full recognition. (by the way, if you want a copy of the official &quot;recipe&quot; for what constitutes a PTSD- e-mail me and I will send you one).(except Nurse Ratchet, I would be too worried that your little woman might read it and get all upset). (yeah, cheap shot I know).<br><br>
Anyway, I always thought PTSD was mostly bullshit used by bums and vets who didn't want to work, wanted benefits, wanted free things, were irresponsible, dead heads, LSD flashbacks, etc.  Remember, I was the long hair pro drug freeko of the 60's too.  But...it all came clear to me one day, doing an evaluation on a old guy for his long term disability medical insurance.  (A bad back patient).  When I was taking his history, his life story and biography, and he told me he was a tail gunner on a B 17 over Germany, he began to cry.  I was stunned. What game was this guy trying to run on me?  As I questionned him more, he began to open up. Seems he had the same dream EVERY NIGHT since WW2 ended. Of being behind his guns as the ship was shot up and bullets were flying, and flames were spreading..  Further questions revealed he had daily flashbacks, DAILY FUCKING FLASHBACKS 50 years later, about planes shooting at him.  Jesus Christ! I was absolutely stunned.  By the time we were done, I knew that he met every criteria, every recipe direction that the DSM required, and that PTSD really did exist.  <br><br>
I got him into help and on meds, and a year later he dropped by. He no longer had the dreams, his family and wife said he was born again, and he just wanted to say thanks.  We both shed a few tears. I felt like a giant. damn me, that was one of the best days ever being a shrink.<br><br>
My wife's best friends husband came back from nam, and could never sit down in the evening. He would come home from &quot;the job&quot; and drink beer until he could pass out into bed. Had 2 kids and a good wife.  But could not stop drinking beer nor sit down once the sun went down.  Tried to talk to him, as a family member, over many beers, but he refused to talk about nam. God fighting mad at me for bring it up even.  Just kept pounding down beers (self medicating).  Finally, last year. his body had enough beer, he went into a hospital and died.<br>
Cause of death was acute liver failure, said the hospital. I say it was Viet Nam and PTSD.This time I felt like shit, a midget, letting someone slip through my fingers even though I knew I could do nothing... <br><br>
Never, never, discount your feelings, your dreams, your reactions, but please, for Tom who didn't make it, and old Freddie, who did, never overlook the need for help, for talk, for fighting (verbal) and for honesty.<br><br>
Let's not lose this site, I for one, certainly need it.  Come on PBS, certainly we are equal to the Three Tenors or some other simpleton artistic stuff that you fund.<br><br>
Chris, I'm out of steam, will address you next (friendly).<br><br>
doc
